See if a causal forest succeeded in capturing heterogeneity by plotting

the TOC and calculating a 95% CI for the AUTOC.

n<-nrow(dfehr)
train <- sample(1:n, n / 2)
X<-covariates
Y<-outcome
W<-Exposure
train.forest <- causal_forest(X[train, ], Y[train], W[train], num.trees = 500)
eval.forest <- causal_forest(X[-train, ], Y[-train], W[-train], num.trees = 500)

tau.hat.train <- predict(train.forest)$predictions
summary(tau.hat.train)
##     Min.  1st Qu.   Median     Mean  3rd Qu.     Max. 
## -0.19582  0.02890  0.06331  0.06179  0.09635  0.39231
boxplot(tau.hat.train,xlab="CSP",ylab="Effects",main="Training",font=18)

tau.hat.test <- predict(eval.forest)$predictions
summary(tau.hat.test)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  0.4666  0.6039  0.6425  0.6463  0.6724  1.1914
boxplot(tau.hat.test,xlab="CSP",ylab="Effects",main="Testing",font=18)

tau.hat.test.df<-data.frame(tau.hat.test)
names(tau.hat.test.df)<-"Effects"
tau.hat.test.df$Group<-"Test"
tau.hat.train.df<-data.frame(tau.hat.train)
names(tau.hat.train.df)<-"Effects"
tau.hat.train.df$Group<-"Train"
head(tau.hat.test.df)
##     Effects Group
## 1 0.6119566  Test
## 2 0.7068333  Test
## 3 0.5588182  Test
## 4 0.6964093  Test
## 5 0.5901060  Test
## 6 0.5907681  Test
tau.hat.df<-rbind(tau.hat.train.df,tau.hat.test.df)

ggplot(tau.hat.df, aes(x=Group, y=Effects)) +geom_boxplot(outlier.colour="black", outlier.shape=16, outlier.size=2, notch=FALSE)+theme_light()+theme_classic(base_size = 18)+theme(legend.position="top")

rate <- rank_average_treatment_effect(eval.forest,
                                      predict(train.forest, X[-train, ])$predictions)
plot(rate)

plot(rate,xlim=range(0.2, 0.8),ylim=range(-1,1))

plot(rate,xlim=range(0.2, 0.4),ylim=range(-1,1))

paste("AUTOC:", round(rate$estimate, 2), "+/", round(1.96 * rate$std.err, 2))
